    "comment_regular_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "The cmdexpand.c change is higher risk, no need to do that here. There are other big changes here that don't need to be mushed into 1 big PR.\r\n\r\nAlso, the `ex_cmds.lua` change raises quite a big maintenance question. For `eval.lua` we have 1 source of truth and the docs are generated from it. Whereas the descs added to `ex_cmds.lua` are a duplicate thing we have to maintain.\r\n\r\nGenerating docs for excmds won't be easy because their docs are spread out everywhere. Instead, a potential idea that unblocks this PR: can `nvim_get_commands` automatically get its `desc` by loading the help files and grabbing all lines until the next blank line? Maybe a crazy idea, but for performance it could be optional:\r\n\r\n    nvim_get_commands({desc=true})\r\n\r\nBenefits:\r\n\r\n1. avoids permanent binary bloat of adding all the text in the `nvim` binary\r\n2. avoids maintenance cost of duplicate docs in `ex_cmds.lua`\r\n3. encourages improving the *actual* docs. The \"short descriptions\" added here should instead be added to the *existing* docs for each excmd, because it makes them more readable. Any excmd doc that doesn't provide a \"short explanation\" as its first N lines is just poorly written.\r\n\r\nLater, we can decide if we want to change how we maintain excmd docs, and then change how `desc` is retrieved at runtime to use the `ex_cmds.lua` map instead of loading help files.",
